ile-type=3D"bitmap" height=3D"268" width=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-element" =
id=3D"mwCA"></a><figcaption id=3D"mwCQ">Optimal route of a salesman visitin=
g the 15 biggest cities in Germany. The route shown is the shortest of the =
 43,589,145,600 possible ones.</figcaption></figure>

<p id=3D"mwCg">The <b id=3D"mwCw">Traveling Salesman Problem</b> (often cal=
led <b id=3D"mwDA">TSP</b>) is a classic algorithmic problem in the field o=
f <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer=
_science" title=3D"Computer science" id=3D"mwDQ">computer science</a> and <=
a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operations_=
research" title=3D"Operations research" id=3D"mwDg">operations research</a>=
.<sup about=3D"#mwt3" class=3D"mw-ref reference" id=3D"cite_ref-1" rel=3D"d=
c:references" typeof=3D"mw:Extension/ref" data-mw=3D"{&quot;name&quot;:&quo=
t;ref&quot;,&quot;attrs&quot;:{},&quot;body&quot;:{&quot;id&quot;:&quot;mw-=
reference-text-cite_note-1&quot;}}"><a href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Travelling_salesman_problem#cite_note-1" id=3D"mwDw"><span class=3D"m=
w-reflink-text" id=3D"mwEA"><span class=3D"cite-bracket" id=3D"mwEQ">[</spa=
n>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket" id=3D"mwEg">]</span></span></a></sup> It is=
 focused on <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Optimization_(computer_science)" title=3D"Optimization (computer science)=
" id=3D"mwEw">optimization</a>. In this context, a <i id=3D"mwFA">better so=
lution</i> often means <i id=3D"mwFQ">a solution that is cheaper, shorter, =
or faster</i>. TSP is a mathematical problem. It is most easily expressed a=
s a <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_=
theory" title=3D"Graph theory" id=3D"mwFg">graph</a> describing the locatio=
ns of a set of <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Node?action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" title=3D"Node (not yet started)" c=
lass=3D"new" typeof=3D"mw:LocalizedAttrs" id=3D"mwFw" data-mw-i18n=3D"{&quo=
t;title&quot;:{&quot;lang&quot;:&quot;x-page&quot;,&quot;key&quot;:&quot;re=
d-link-title&quot;,&quot;params&quot;:[&quot;Node&quot;]}}">nodes</a>.</p>

<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb" id=3D"mwGA"><a h=
ref=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:William_Rowan_Hamilton_painti=
ng.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description" id=3D"mwGQ"><img resource=3D"//simple=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:William_Rowan_Hamilton_painting.jpg" src=3D"https:=
//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/William_Rowan_Hamilton_=
painting.jpg/250px-William_Rowan_Hamilton_painting.jpg" decoding=3D"async" =
data-file-width=3D"640" data-file-height=3D"768" data-file-type=3D"bitmap" =
height=3D"300" width=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-element" id=3D"mwGg"></a><fig=
caption id=3D"mwGw">William Rowan Hamilton</figcaption></figure><p id=3D"mw=
HA">The traveling salesman problem was defined in the 1800s by the Irish ma=
thematician <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/William_Rowan_Hamilton" title=3D"William Rowan Hamilton" id=3D"mwHQ">W. R=
. Hamilton</a> and by the British mathematician <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=
=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Kirkman?action=3Dedit&amp;redl=
ink=3D1" title=3D"Thomas Kirkman (not yet started)" class=3D"new" typeof=3D=
"mw:LocalizedAttrs" id=3D"mwHg" data-mw-i18n=3D"{&quot;title&quot;:{&quot;l=
ang&quot;:&quot;x-page&quot;,&quot;key&quot;:&quot;red-link-title&quot;,&qu=
ot;params&quot;:[&quot;Thomas Kirkman&quot;]}}">Thomas Kirkman</a>. Hamilto=
n=E2=80=99s <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Icosian_Game?action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" title=3D"Icosian Game (not ye=
t started)" class=3D"new" typeof=3D"mw:LocalizedAttrs" id=3D"mwHw" data-mw-=
i18n=3D"{&quot;title&quot;:{&quot;lang&quot;:&quot;x-page&quot;,&quot;key&q=
uot;:&quot;red-link-title&quot;,&quot;params&quot;:[&quot;Icosian Game&quot=
;]}}">Icosian Game</a> was a recreational puzzle based on finding a <a rel=
=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hamiltonian_cycl=
e" title=3D"Hamiltonian cycle" class=3D"mw-redirect" id=3D"mwIA">Hamiltonia=
n cycle</a>.<sup about=3D"#mwt4" class=3D"mw-ref reference" id=3D"cite_ref-=
2" rel=3D"dc:references" typeof=3D"mw:Extension/ref" data-mw=3D"{&quot;name=
&quot;:&quot;ref&quot;,&quot;attrs&quot;:{},&quot;body&quot;:{&quot;id&quot=
;:&quot;mw-reference-text-cite_note-2&quot;}}"><a href=3D"https://simple.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Travelling_salesman_problem#cite_note-2" id=3D"mwIQ"><span=
 class=3D"mw-reflink-text" id=3D"mwIg"><span class=3D"cite-bracket" id=3D"m=
wIw">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket" id=3D"mwJA">]</span></span></a><=
/sup> The general form of the TSP appears to have been first studied by mat=
hematicians during the 1930s in Vienna and at Harvard, notably by <a rel=3D=
"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Menger?action=
=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" title=3D"Karl Menger (not yet started)" class=3D"n=
ew" typeof=3D"mw:LocalizedAttrs" id=3D"mwJQ" data-mw-i18n=3D"{&quot;title&q=
uot;:{&quot;lang&quot;:&quot;x-page&quot;,&quot;key&quot;:&quot;red-link-ti=
tle&quot;,&quot;params&quot;:[&quot;Karl Menger&quot;]}}">Karl Menger</a>. =
Menger defines the problem, considers the obvious brute-force algorithm, an=
d observes the non-optimality of the <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https:/=
/simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nearest_neighbour_algorithm" title=3D"Nearest ne=
ighbour algorithm" id=3D"mwJg">nearest neighbour</a> <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink"=
 href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heuristic" title=3D"Heuristic" i=
d=3D"mwJw">heuristic</a>:</p><blockquote id=3D"mwKA"><p id=3D"mwKQ">We deno=
te by <i id=3D"mwKg">messenger problem</i> (since in practice this question=
 should be solved by each postman, anyway also by many travelers) the task =
to find, for <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Finite_set" title=3D"Finite set" id=3D"mwKw">=EF=AC=81nitely</a> many po=
ints whose pairwise distances are known, the shortest route connecting the =
points. Of course, this problem is solvable by finitely many trials. Rules =
which would push the number of trials below the number of <a rel=3D"mw:Wiki=
Link" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permutation" title=3D"Permu=
tation" id=3D"mwLA">permutations</a> of the given points, are not known. Th=
e rule that one first should go from the starting point to the closest poin=
t, then to the point closest to this, etc., in general does not yield the s=
hortest route.</p></blockquote><p id=3D"mwLQ"><a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=
=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hassler_Whitney?action=3Dedit&amp;red=
link=3D1" title=3D"Hassler Whitney (not yet started)" class=3D"new" typeof=
=3D"mw:LocalizedAttrs" id=3D"mwLg" data-mw-i18n=3D"{&quot;title&quot;:{&quo=
t;lang&quot;:&quot;x-page&quot;,&quot;key&quot;:&quot;red-link-title&quot;,=
&quot;params&quot;:[&quot;Hassler Whitney&quot;]}}">Hassler Whitney</a> at =
<a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princeton_=
University" title=3D"Princeton University" id=3D"mwLw">Princeton University=
</a> introduced the name <i id=3D"mwMA">traveling salesman problem</i> soon=
 after.<sup about=3D"#mwt5" class=3D"mw-ref reference" id=3D"cite_ref-3" re=
l=3D"dc:references" typeof=3D"mw:Extension/ref" data-mw=3D"{&quot;name&quot=
;:&quot;ref&quot;,&quot;attrs&quot;:{},&quot;body&quot;:{&quot;id&quot;:&qu=
ot;mw-reference-text-cite_note-3&quot;}}"><a href=3D"https://simple.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Travelling_salesman_problem#cite_note-3" id=3D"mwMQ"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-reflink-text" id=3D"mwMg"><span class=3D"cite-bracket" id=3D"mwMw">=
[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket" id=3D"mwNA">]</span></span></a></sup>=
</p>

<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc" id=3D"mwNQ" data-mw=3D"{&quot;autoGenera=
ted&quot;:true}"></section><section data-mw-section-id=3D"1" id=3D"mwNg"><d=
iv class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2" id=3D"mwAA"><h2 id=3D"Stating_the_probl=
em">Stating the problem</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection" id=3D"mwiA"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket" id=3D"mwiQ">[</span><a href=3D"https://s=
imple.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTravelling_salesman_problem&amp;vea=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Change section: Stating the problem"=
 class=3D"mw-editsection-visualeditor" id=3D"mwig"><span id=3D"mwiw">change=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-divider" id=3D"mwjA"> | </span><a =
href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTravelling_salesma=
n_problem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section's source=
 code: Stating the problem" id=3D"mwjQ"><span id=3D"mwjg">change source</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket" id=3D"mwjw">]</span></span></=
div>
<p id=3D"mwNw">The Travelling Salesman Problem describes a salesman who mus=
t travel between N cities. The order in which he does so is something he do=
es not care about, as long as he visits each once during his trip, and fini=
shes where he was at first. Each city is connected to other close by cities=
, or nodes, by <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Airplane" title=3D"Airplane" id=3D"mwOA">airplanes</a>, or by <a rel=
=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Road" title=3D"R=
oad" id=3D"mwOQ">road</a> or <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Railway" title=3D"Railway" class=3D"mw-redirect" id=3D"m=
wOg">railway</a>. Each of those links between the cities has one or more we=
ights (or the cost) attached. The cost describes how "difficult" it is to t=
raverse this edge on the graph, and may be given, for example, by the cost =
of an airplane ticket or train ticket, or perhaps by the length of the edge=
, or time required to complete the traversal. The salesman wants to keep bo=
th the travel costs and the <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Distance" title=3D"Distance" id=3D"mwOw">distance</a> he =
travels as low as possible.</p>

<p id=3D"mwPA">The Traveling Salesman Problem is typical of a large class o=
f "hard" optimization problems that have intrigued mathematicians and compu=
ter scientists for years. Most important, it has applications in science an=
d engineering. For example, in the manufacture of a circuit board, it is im=
portant to determine the best order in which a laser will drill thousands o=
f holes. An efficient solution to this problem reduces production costs for=
 the manufacturer.</p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id=3D"2" id=3D"mwPQ"><div class=3D"mw-he=
ading mw-heading2" id=3D"mwkA"><h2 id=3D"Difficulty">Difficulty</h2><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection" id=3D"mwkQ"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket" =
id=3D"mwkg">[</span><a href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?tit=
le=3DTravelling_salesman_problem&amp;veaction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=
=3D"Change section: Difficulty" class=3D"mw-editsection-visualeditor" id=3D=
"mwkw"><span id=3D"mwlA">change</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-div=
ider" id=3D"mwlQ"> | </span><a href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/w/index=
.php?title=3DTravelling_salesman_problem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2"=
 title=3D"Edit section's source code: Difficulty" id=3D"mwlg"><span id=3D"m=
wlw">change source</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket" id=3D"m=
wmA">]</span></span></div>
<p id=3D"mwPg">In general, the traveling salesman problem is hard to solve.=
 If there is a way to break this problem into smaller component problems, t=
he components will be at least as complex as the original one. This is what=
 computer <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Scientists" title=3D"Scientists" class=3D"mw-redirect" id=3D"mwPw">scientis=
ts</a> call <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/NP-hardness" title=3D"NP-hardness" id=3D"mwQA">NP</a>-hard problems.</p>

<p id=3D"mwQQ">Many people have studied this problem. The easiest (and most=
 expensive solution) is to simply try all possibilities. The problem with t=
his is that for N cities you have (N-1) <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"http=
s://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factorial" title=3D"Factorial" id=3D"mwQg">fa=
ctorial</a> possibilities. This means that for only 10 cities there are ove=
r 180 thousand <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Combination" title=3D"Combination" class=3D"mw-disambig" id=3D"mwQw">c=
ombinations</a> to try (since the start city is defined, there can be permu=
tations on the remaining nine). We only count half since each route has an =
equal route in reverse with the same length or cost.
9! / 2 =3D 181 440</p>
<ul id=3D"mwRA"><li id=3D"mwRQ">Exact solutions to the problem can be found=
, using <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink/Interwiki" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Branch_and_bound" title=3D"en:Branch and bound" class=3D"extiw" id=3D"m=
wRg">branch and bound</a> <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm" id=3D"mwRw">algorithms</a>.<=
sup about=3D"#mwt7" class=3D"mw-ref reference" id=3D"cite_ref-4" rel=3D"dc:=
references" typeof=3D"mw:Extension/ref" data-mw=3D"{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;=
ref&quot;,&quot;attrs&quot;:{},&quot;body&quot;:{&quot;id&quot;:&quot;mw-re=
ference-text-cite_note-4&quot;}}"><a href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Travelling_salesman_problem#cite_note-4" id=3D"mwSA"><span class=3D"mw-=
reflink-text" id=3D"mwSQ"><span class=3D"cite-bracket" id=3D"mwSg">[</span>=
4<span class=3D"cite-bracket" id=3D"mwSw">]</span></span></a></sup> This is=
 currently possible for up to 85,900 cities.<sup about=3D"#mwt10" class=3D"=
mw-ref reference" id=3D"cite_ref-5" rel=3D"dc:references" typeof=3D"mw:Exte=
nsion/ref" data-mw=3D"{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;ref&quot;,&quot;attrs&quot;:{=
},&quot;body&quot;:{&quot;id&quot;:&quot;mw-reference-text-cite_note-5&quot=
;}}"><a href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Travelling_salesman_probl=
em#cite_note-5" id=3D"mwTA"><span class=3D"mw-reflink-text" id=3D"mwTQ"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket" id=3D"mwTg">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
 id=3D"mwTw">]</span></span></a></sup></li>
<li id=3D"mwUA"><a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Heuristic" title=3D"Heuristic" id=3D"mwUQ">Heuristics</a> approaches =
use a set of guiding rules for selection of the next node. But since heuris=
tics result in <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Approximation" title=3D"Approximation" id=3D"mwUg">approximations</a>,=
 they will not always give the <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simpl=
e.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optimal" title=3D"Optimal" class=3D"mw-redirect" id=3D=
"mwUw">optimal</a> solution, although high quality admissible heuristics ca=
n find a useful solution in a fraction of the time required for a full <a r=
el=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brute_force_at=
tack" title=3D"Brute force attack" id=3D"mwVA">brute force</a> of the probl=
em. An example of a heuristic for a node would be a summation of how many u=
nvisited nodes are "close by" a connected node. This could encourage the sa=
lesman to visit a group of close by nodes clustered together before moving =
onto another natural cluster in the graph. See <a rel=3D"mw:WikiLink" href=
=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_algorithm" title=3D"Monte=
 Carlo algorithm" id=3D"mwVQ">Monte Carlo algorithms</a> and <a rel=3D"mw:W=
ikiLink" href=3D"https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Las_Vegas_algorithm" tit=
le=3D"Las Vegas algorithm" id=3D"mwVg">Las Vegas algorithms</a></li></ul>

